# I \- Using Kafka:

## Creating a topic:

Run this command: `kafka-topics.sh --create --topic Hello-Kafka --replication-factor 1 --partitions 1 --bootstrap-server localhost:9092`  
Here is the output:  
![][image11]  
Check if the topic was created:  
![][image12]  
Once the topic is created, we can test it using a  dummy producer and consumer provided by Kafka itself using:

- `kafka-console-producer.sh`  
- `kafka-console-consumer.sh`

Here are the commands to execute. First, attach 2 shells to the master node:

- `kafka-console-producer.sh --broker-list localhost:9092 --topic Hello-Kafka`  
- `kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --topic Hello-Kafka --from-beginning`

`![][image13]`

Here are the results:  
![][image14]

It supports UTF-8\! Even emojis are accepted.

## Set up with multiple brokers:

In the above, we configured Kafka to launch a single broker. To create multiple brokers, simply duplicate the $KAFKA\_HOME/config/server.properties file as many times as needed. In our case, we will create two other files: server-one.properties and server-two.properties, then modify the following parameters as follows:

![][image15]  
What we need to do is duplicate the file server.properties. Use this command:

- cp /usr/local/kafka/config/server.properties /usr/local/kafka/config/server-one.properties && cp /usr/local/kafka/config/server.properties /usr/local/kafka/config/server-two.properties 

Now, for each one of these new files, we have to make some changes. Use your favourite text editor and set these changes:

- For this file, `“server-one.properties”,` set these options:  
  - broker.id \= 1  
  - listeners=`PLAINTEXT://localhost:9093`  
  - log.dirs=`/tmp/kafka-logs-1`   
- For this file, `“server-two.properties”,` set these options:  
  - broker.id \= 2  
  - listeners=`PLAINTEXT://localhost:9094`  
  - log.dirs=`/tmp/kafka-logs-2`

Start the brokers using this command:  
`kafka-server-start.sh $KAFKA_HOME/config/server.properties &`  
 `kafka-server-start.sh $KAFKA_HOME/config/server-one.properties &`  
 `kafka-server-start.sh $KAFKA_HOME/config/server-two.properties &`

After running this command, we test again with `jps` command, and it shows us:  
![][image16]  
There are 3 Kafka brokers and 1 Zookeeper working.

# Kafka Integration with Spark

First let’s build the project with:  
`mvn clean compile assembly:single`  
`![][image24]`  
Then copy it to docker hadoop-master container using this command:  
`docker cp target/stream-kafka-spark-1-jar-with-dependencies.jar hadoop-master:/root/stream-kafka.jar`

`![][image25]`

After all of this start the Spark Streaming listener:

`spark-submit --class spark.kafka.SparkKafkaWordCount --master local  stream-kafka.jar localhost:9092 Hello-Kafka mySparkConsumerGroup >> out`

Attach another shell to Docker and run this command to send messages and see the streaming result:

`kafka-console-producer.sh --broker-list localhost:9092 --topic Hello-Kafka`

After all of this running `tail -f out` shows this:  
![][image26]
